/* Workplace English Data — Part 3: Meetings & Reflections */
(function() {
  if (typeof WORKPLACE_ENGLISH === 'undefined') return;

  // ============================================================
  // MODULE 4: MEETINGS & PROFESSIONAL DISCUSSIONS
  // ============================================================
  WORKPLACE_ENGLISH.meetingsExplanations = {
    title: "Meetings & Professional Discussions",
    sections: [
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      // 4.1 Contributing Ideas in Meetings
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      {
        id: "contributing-ideas",
        title: "Contributing Ideas in Meetings",
        theory: "Australian staff meetings value contribution from everyone. Use phrases like 'I'd like to suggest...', 'One thing that's worked for me is...', 'Building on what Sarah said...'. Chinese speakers sometimes wait to be invited to speak \u2014 in Australia, you're expected to contribute proactively. Volunteering your ideas shows engagement and professionalism. You don't need to wait for the chair to call on you.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"mi001",type:"fill",q:"I'd like to ___ that we trial peer observation this term to help build our ___ practice.",a:"suggest ... classroom",exp:"'I'd like to suggest' is the standard polite way to raise an idea in a staff meeting. 'Classroom practice' is a common collocation in Australian education."},
          {id:"mi002",type:"mc",q:"Which is the most appropriate way to introduce an idea in a staff meeting?",options:["I think you're all doing it wrong.","One thing that's worked in my class is flexible seating.","You should try what I do.","Nobody has thought of this but me."],a:1,exp:"'One thing that's worked for me is...' shares personal experience without imposing. It's collaborative and humble \u2014 valued in Australian workplaces."},
          {id:"mi003",type:"error",q:"I have a suggest about how we can improve the homework policy.",a:"I have a suggestion about how we can improve the homework policy.",exp:"'Suggestion' is the noun form; 'suggest' is the verb. Chinese speakers sometimes confuse parts of speech because Mandarin words often function as both."},
          {id:"mi004",type:"fill",q:"Building on what Priya ___, I think we could also ___ a parent information evening on digital safety.",a:"said ... organise",exp:"'Building on what [Name] said' credits a colleague while adding your own idea. 'Organise' uses Australian spelling (not 'organize')."},
          {id:"mi005",type:"mc",q:"What does 'I'll throw something out there' mean in a meeting?",options:["I want to discard an item","I'll present an idea for the group to consider","I'm going to leave the meeting","I want to argue with someone"],a:1,exp:"'Throw something out there' is an informal Australian expression meaning to suggest an idea for discussion, without claiming it is the best option."},
          {id:"mi006",type:"fill",q:"Could I ___ something? I've been thinking about how we ___ differentiate our assessment tasks.",a:"add ... might",exp:"'Could I add something?' is a polite way to contribute without interrupting. 'Might' is softer than 'should' when proposing changes."},
          {id:"mi007",type:"error",q:"I want to say my opinion about the new timetable change.",a:"I'd like to share my thoughts on the new timetable change.",exp:"'I'd like to share my thoughts on...' is more professional than 'I want to say my opinion about'. 'Thoughts' is softer than 'opinion' in a meeting context."},
          {id:"mi008",type:"fill",q:"Has anyone ___ using Sentral to track student ___ across different KLAs?",a:"considered ... progress",exp:"'Has anyone considered' invites group reflection. Sentral is the student management system used in many NSW schools. 'KLAs' = Key Learning Areas."},
          {id:"mi009",type:"mc",q:"You want to volunteer to lead a new initiative. Which phrasing is best?",options:["Someone needs to do this, so I guess I will.","I'd be happy to take the lead on that if no one else has put their hand up.","I'll do it because none of you will.","The principal should assign someone."],a:1,exp:"'I'd be happy to take the lead' shows willingness without arrogance. 'If no one else has put their hand up' is considerate of others."},
          {id:"mi010",type:"fill",q:"I ___ we look at the data from last term's NAPLAN results before we ___ any changes.",a:"suggest ... make",exp:"'I suggest we look at the data' is evidence-based and professional. NAPLAN is Australia's national literacy and numeracy assessment programme."},
          {id:"mi011",type:"open",q:"Write a contribution to a staff meeting about improving lunchtime supervision.",a:"I'd like to raise something about lunchtime supervision. I've noticed that the area near the basketball courts is often unsupervised, and that's where most of the incidents seem to happen. Could we look at adjusting the duty roster so that spot gets better coverage? I'm happy to take one of those shifts if it helps.",exp:"A good meeting contribution identifies the problem, provides evidence, suggests a solution, and offers personal commitment."},
          {id:"mi012",type:"fill",q:"That's a really ___ point, and I think it ___ to our Year 8 cohort as well.",a:"valid ... applies",exp:"'Valid point' acknowledges a colleague. 'Applies to' means is relevant to. Building on others' ideas strengthens team discussion."},
          {id:"mi013",type:"error",q:"I am agree with the idea to change the bell times.",a:"I agree with the idea of changing the bell times.",exp:"'Agree' does not take 'am' before it \u2014 it is not a passive verb. 'The idea of changing' uses the gerund after 'of'. Common Chinese speaker error from \u6211\u540c\u610f."},
          {id:"mi014",type:"fill",q:"In my ___ year school, we used to run a buddy programme between Year 7 and Year 12. It worked really well for student ___.",a:"previous ... wellbeing",exp:"Sharing experience from previous workplaces is valuable. 'Wellbeing' is one word in Australian English and is a key priority in NSW schools."},
          {id:"mi015",type:"mc",q:"What is the best way to support a colleague's idea in a meeting?",options:["Just nod silently","Say 'I really like that idea. It would address the issue we've been having with...'","Say 'Good' and move on","Wait until after the meeting to agree privately"],a:1,exp:"Publicly supporting an idea with a specific reason ('It would address...') strengthens the proposal and shows collaborative thinking. Silent nodding is easily missed."},
          {id:"mi016",type:"fill",q:"One thing I've ___ in my classroom is using exit tickets, and the ___ has been really positive.",a:"trialled ... feedback",exp:"'Trialled' is Australian spelling for tested/piloted. 'Exit tickets' are quick end-of-lesson checks. Sharing what works builds collective expertise."},
          {id:"mi017",type:"error",q:"What if we will try to use the library space for the Year 9 project?",a:"What if we tried using the library space for the Year 9 project?",exp:"'What if we tried' uses the past tense for a hypothetical suggestion (second conditional). 'Will try' is not correct in a 'what if' structure."},
          {id:"mi018",type:"fill",q:"I've been doing some ___ into restorative justice approaches, and I think it could really ___ our behaviour management.",a:"reading ... improve",exp:"'Doing some reading into' shows you've done homework on the topic. It adds credibility to your suggestion in a meeting."},
          {id:"mi019",type:"mc",q:"A colleague proposes an idea you've already tried and it didn't work. What do you say?",options:["That won't work. I tried it already.","That's interesting. I tried something similar and found that... Would it help if I shared what I learned?","Don't bother. It'll fail.","Just let them find out for themselves."],a:1,exp:"Sharing your experience constructively helps the team without shutting down the idea. They may adapt it successfully."},
          {id:"mi020",type:"fill",q:"Sorry to ___ in, but could I quickly ___ a point about the excursion logistics?",a:"jump ... raise",exp:"'Sorry to jump in' is a polite Australian way to interject. 'Raise a point' means bring up a topic for discussion."},
          {id:"mi021",type:"fill",q:"I reckon we should ___ the student voice survey before making any decisions about the ___ policy.",a:"review ... uniform",exp:"'I reckon' is characteristically Australian and acceptable in semi-formal meetings. It means 'I think'. 'Student voice' = getting student input."},
          {id:"mi022",type:"error",q:"I think is important that we discuss about the assessment schedule.",a:"I think it is important that we discuss the assessment schedule.",exp:"'I think it is important' needs the pronoun 'it'. 'Discuss' does not take 'about' \u2014 it is a transitive verb. Both are common Chinese speaker errors."},
          {id:"mi023",type:"fill",q:"Could we ___ some time at the next meeting to ___ how the new reporting system is going?",a:"set aside ... review",exp:"'Set aside some time' is a professional way to request agenda space. 'Review how it is going' = evaluate progress."},
          {id:"mi024",type:"mc",q:"What does 'Let's park that for now' mean in a meeting?",options:["Let's go to the car park","Let's put that topic aside and return to it later","Let's reject that idea permanently","Let's take a vote on it"],a:1,exp:"'Park that for now' means set it aside temporarily \u2014 the topic is not rejected, just deferred. It is common in Australian professional meetings."},
          {id:"mi025",type:"fill",q:"I ___ that we pilot the programme with one year group first and then ___ it based on the results.",a:"propose ... evaluate",exp:"'Propose' is more formal than 'suggest'. A pilot approach is practical \u2014 it shows strategic thinking."},
          {id:"mi026",type:"open",q:"Write a contribution to a meeting about integrating more Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander perspectives into the curriculum.",a:"I've been reflecting on how we embed Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander perspectives across our KLAs. I'd like to suggest we start by auditing our current resources to identify gaps. We could also reach out to our local Aboriginal Education Consultative Group for guidance on culturally appropriate content. I'm happy to coordinate this for the Technology faculty if that would help.",exp:"This contribution is culturally respectful, action-oriented, and offers personal follow-through. It references the AECG, which is a key consultation body in NSW."},
          {id:"mi027",type:"fill",q:"Just to ___ what we've discussed so far \u2014 we're looking at three ___ for the fundraiser.",a:"summarise ... options",exp:"'Just to summarise' is a useful meeting phrase that helps keep discussion on track. 'Options' shows that no decision has been made yet."},
          {id:"mi028",type:"error",q:"I would like to propose we should to create a mentoring programme for beginning teachers.",a:"I would like to propose that we create a mentoring programme for beginning teachers.",exp:"'Propose that we create' uses the subjunctive (base form after 'that'). No 'should to' \u2014 'should' never takes 'to'. 'Programme' is Australian spelling."},
          {id:"mi029",type:"fill",q:"Has the ___ team considered using data from the Tell Them From Me survey to ___ our wellbeing strategy?",a:"executive ... inform",exp:"'Executive team' = school leadership. 'Tell Them From Me' is a NSW student wellbeing survey. 'Inform' means to guide decision-making based on evidence."},
          {id:"mi030",type:"mc",q:"You have a good idea but feel nervous sharing it. What should you do?",options:["Stay silent and email it to the principal later","Say 'I'm not sure if this is a good idea, but...' and share it","Write it down and give it to a confident colleague to say","Say 'I'd like to suggest...' and state it clearly"],a:3,exp:"'I'd like to suggest...' is clear and professional. Starting with 'I'm not sure if this is good' undermines your own idea before you even say it."},
          {id:"mi031",type:"fill",q:"I think we need to be ___ about what 'differentiation' looks like in ___, not just in theory.",a:"specific ... practice",exp:"'In practice' vs 'in theory' is a powerful professional distinction. Being specific makes discussion more productive."},
          {id:"mi032",type:"error",q:"Can I to say something? I think we are not spend enough time on literacy.",a:"Can I say something? I think we are not spending enough time on literacy.",exp:"No 'to' after 'can'. 'Are not spending' = present continuous. 'Spend' alone is incorrect after 'are'. Two errors common for Chinese speakers."},
          {id:"mi033",type:"fill",q:"I'd like to ___ the idea of creating a shared resource bank on Google Drive for our ___.",a:"float ... faculty",exp:"'Float an idea' means propose it casually for group reaction. 'Faculty' is the Australian term for a department in a school."},
          {id:"mi034",type:"mc",q:"What is the most effective way to contribute to a meeting when you are new to a school?",options:["Stay completely silent for the first term","Criticise existing practices to show your expertise","Share what you've observed and ask thoughtful questions","Dominate the conversation to make a strong first impression"],a:2,exp:"New teachers build credibility by sharing observations and asking questions. It shows engagement without presuming expertise about the school's culture."},
          {id:"mi035",type:"fill",q:"I noticed that ___ attendance has dropped for Year 10 this term. Could we ___ possible reasons at our next faculty meeting?",a:"lesson ... explore",exp:"Using data ('attendance has dropped') to frame a discussion point is evidence-based. 'Explore possible reasons' invites collaborative problem-solving."},
          {id:"mi036",type:"open",q:"Write a meeting contribution proposing a whole-school approach to mobile phone management.",a:"I'd like to raise the issue of mobile phone management. At the moment, each teacher seems to have a different approach, and students are confused about expectations. I'd like to suggest we develop a consistent whole-school policy. Perhaps we could survey staff and students first to understand the current situation, and then form a working party to draft guidelines. I'm happy to help with the survey design.",exp:"A strong proposal: identifies the problem, acknowledges different perspectives, suggests a process, and offers personal contribution."},
          {id:"mi037",type:"fill",q:"Before we move on, could I just ___ back to the point about ___ allocation?",a:"come ... resource",exp:"'Come back to' means return to a previous topic. It is useful when something was parked earlier. 'Resource allocation' is a common school planning term."},
          {id:"mi038",type:"error",q:"I have been notice that many student are struggle with time management.",a:"I have noticed that many students are struggling with time management.",exp:"'Have noticed' = present perfect. 'Students' = plural noun. 'Are struggling' = present continuous. Multiple errors from Chinese grammar transfer."}
        ]
      },

      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      // 4.2 Asking for Clarification
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      {
        id: "asking-clarification",
        title: "Asking for Clarification",
        theory: "Asking for clarification is seen as engaged and professional, not as a sign of weakness. Use 'Sorry, could you clarify what you mean by...?', 'Just to make sure I understand...', 'When you say X, do you mean...?'. Chinese speakers sometimes nod along rather than ask \u2014 this can lead to misunderstandings. In Australian professional settings, clarifying shows you care about getting things right.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"ac001",type:"fill",q:"Sorry, could you ___ what you mean by 'adjusted scope and sequence'? I want to make sure I ___ correctly.",a:"clarify ... understand",exp:"'Could you clarify' is polite and professional. 'I want to make sure I understand' frames the request positively."},
          {id:"ac002",type:"mc",q:"Your head teacher says 'We need to unpack the syllabus outcomes for Stage 4.' You're not sure what 'unpack' means here. What do you say?",options:["I don't understand English very well.","When you say 'unpack', do you mean break them down into specific learning goals?","What?","I'll just figure it out myself."],a:1,exp:"'When you say X, do you mean Y?' checks understanding by paraphrasing. It shows you are engaged and trying to understand, not that your English is weak."},
          {id:"ac003",type:"error",q:"Can you repeat again what you said about the new marking criteria?",a:"Could you repeat what you said about the new marking criteria?",exp:"'Repeat again' is redundant \u2014 'repeat' already means 'say again'. Also, 'Could you' is more polite than 'Can you' in a professional setting."},
          {id:"ac004",type:"fill",q:"Just to ___ sure I've got this right \u2014 you're saying that all ___ tasks need to be moderated by Week 8?",a:"make ... assessment",exp:"'Just to make sure I've got this right' is an excellent clarification opener. It recaps what you heard for confirmation."},
          {id:"ac005",type:"mc",q:"Which phrase is most appropriate for asking a question in a whole-staff briefing?",options:["That makes no sense to me.","Could I just check \u2014 does that apply to casual teachers as well?","You didn't explain that properly.","Huh?"],a:1,exp:"'Could I just check' is polite and specific. It asks a targeted question rather than making a general complaint about the explanation."},
          {id:"ac006",type:"fill",q:"I'm not quite ___ I follow. When you say 'cross-curricular', are you referring to ___ across different subjects?",a:"sure ... collaboration",exp:"'I'm not quite sure I follow' is a sophisticated way to say 'I don't fully understand'. It protects the speaker from feeling incompetent."},
          {id:"ac007",type:"error",q:"Excuse me, what means 'formative assessment' in this context?",a:"Excuse me, what does 'formative assessment' mean in this context?",exp:"English questions need auxiliary verbs: 'What does X mean?' not 'What means X?' This word order error transfers directly from Mandarin question structure."},
          {id:"ac008",type:"fill",q:"Could you give me an ___ of what that might look like in a Year 7 ___?",a:"example ... classroom",exp:"'Give me an example' makes abstract concepts concrete. It is a powerful clarification strategy that helps visual and practical learners."},
          {id:"ac009",type:"mc",q:"A deputy principal uses the acronym 'QTF' in a meeting. You don't know what it stands for. What do you do?",options:["Pretend you know and look it up later","Ask 'Sorry, I'm not familiar with that acronym. Could you tell me what QTF stands for?'","Whisper to the person next to you","Ignore it and hope it's not important"],a:1,exp:"Asking about acronyms is completely normal. QTF stands for Quality Teaching Framework, a key NSW pedagogical framework. Never pretend to know."},
          {id:"ac010",type:"fill",q:"Sorry to ___ you there \u2014 when you mentioned the new ___ platform, which one were you referring to?",a:"stop ... reporting",exp:"'Sorry to stop you there' politely pauses the speaker. Asking 'which one' shows you need specifics, not the general concept."},
          {id:"ac011",type:"fill",q:"I want to make sure I'm on the ___ page. Are we talking about changing the ___ for all year groups or just Stage 5?",a:"same ... timetable",exp:"'On the same page' means having the same understanding. Confirming scope (all year groups vs just Stage 5) prevents misunderstandings."},
          {id:"ac012",type:"error",q:"Can you explain me what is the difference between summative and formative assessment?",a:"Can you explain to me what the difference is between summative and formative assessment?",exp:"'Explain to me' requires 'to'. Embedded question word order: 'what the difference is' not 'what is the difference'. Both are Mandarin transfer errors."},
          {id:"ac013",type:"open",q:"Write a clarification question about a new school policy on student device usage that was explained too quickly.",a:"Sorry, could I just go back to the device policy for a moment? I want to make sure I understand the rules correctly. Are students allowed to use their personal devices during class time, or only school-issued laptops? And does this apply to all year groups, or just senior students?",exp:"Good clarification: politely requests to revisit the topic, states the reason, and asks two specific questions to resolve ambiguity."},
          {id:"ac014",type:"fill",q:"Just to ___ \u2014 when you say the report is due Friday, do you mean ___ of business Friday or the start of the day?",a:"confirm ... end",exp:"Clarifying deadlines prevents missed submissions. 'End of business' (EOB) is a common professional term meaning the end of the working day."},
          {id:"ac015",type:"mc",q:"You're in a professional learning session and the presenter uses a term you don't know. What is the best approach?",options:["Don't ask because everyone else seems to understand","Write down the term and ask the presenter during a break","Leave the session and look it up online","Shout out the question immediately"],a:1,exp:"Noting it down and asking during a break is respectful of the session flow while still ensuring you learn. You could also ask a colleague quietly."},
          {id:"ac016",type:"fill",q:"When you say 'evidence-based practice', are you talking about ___ research or classroom observation ___?",a:"academic ... data",exp:"Clarifying the type of evidence expected helps you prepare appropriately. Academic research and classroom data are different forms of evidence."},
          {id:"ac017",type:"error",q:"Sorry, I didn't catch it. Can you say one more time?",a:"Sorry, I didn't catch that. Could you say that one more time?",exp:"'Didn't catch that' (not 'it'). 'Could you say that one more time' needs the demonstrative 'that'. 'Could' is more polite than 'can'."},
          {id:"ac018",type:"fill",q:"I'm still a bit ___ about the timeline. Could you walk me ___ the key dates again?",a:"unclear ... through",exp:"'Walk me through' means explain step by step. 'A bit unclear' is a gentle way to say you don't understand, avoiding direct 'I don't know'."},
          {id:"ac019",type:"mc",q:"Which of these is NOT a good clarification strategy?",options:["Paraphrasing what you heard","Asking for a specific example","Nodding and pretending to understand","Asking the speaker to repeat a key point"],a:2,exp:"Nodding and pretending to understand is the worst strategy. It leads to misunderstandings and missed information. All other options are effective."},
          {id:"ac020",type:"fill",q:"So if I ___ you correctly, we need to submit our programmes by the end of ___ 5?",a:"understand ... Week",exp:"'If I understand you correctly' is a classic clarification check. 'Programmes' uses Australian spelling. School terms are divided into weeks in NSW."},
          {id:"ac021",type:"fill",q:"Could you ___ on what you mean by 'adjusting the curriculum'? I'm not sure how ___ that change should be.",a:"elaborate ... significant",exp:"'Elaborate on' means explain in more detail. 'How significant' asks about the scale of the change \u2014 a smart clarification question."},
          {id:"ac022",type:"error",q:"What you mean by 'differentiated instruction'? I am not sure I understand the meaning.",a:"What do you mean by 'differentiated instruction'? I'm not sure I understand.",exp:"Questions need 'do': 'What do you mean'. 'I'm not sure I understand' is sufficient \u2014 'the meaning' is redundant after 'understand'."},
          {id:"ac023",type:"fill",q:"Sorry, I missed the first part. Could you go ___ to what you said about the NESA ___ requirements?",a:"back ... registration",exp:"'Go back to' revisits a topic. NESA registration requirements are important for NSW teachers \u2014 they include hours of professional development."},
          {id:"ac024",type:"mc",q:"A colleague says 'We should align our teaching with the Standards.' Which clarification question is most useful?",options:["What are standards?","Which specific Standards are you referring to \u2014 the Australian Professional Standards for Teachers or the curriculum standards?","Why should we do that?","Can you say that in Chinese?"],a:1,exp:"There are multiple 'standards' in Australian education. Clarifying which ones (Professional Standards vs curriculum standards) prevents confusion."},
          {id:"ac025",type:"fill",q:"I'm sorry, I didn't quite ___ that. Could you speak a little more ___, please?",a:"catch ... slowly",exp:"'Didn't quite catch that' is a natural way to ask someone to repeat. 'A little more slowly' is a polite request that doesn't blame the speaker."},
          {id:"ac026",type:"open",q:"Write a clarification question for a staff meeting where the principal mentioned a new 'cross-KLA literacy strategy' but didn't explain the details.",a:"Thank you for raising the cross-KLA literacy strategy. I'd like to understand more about what this looks like in practice. Could you clarify whether each faculty is expected to develop its own approach, or will there be a whole-school framework? Also, is there professional learning planned to support us with this?",exp:"This clarification thanks the speaker, asks two specific questions about implementation and support, and shows proactive thinking."},
          {id:"ac027",type:"fill",q:"Just so I'm ___ \u2014 the professional learning day on the 15th is ___, not optional?",a:"clear ... compulsory",exp:"'Just so I'm clear' frames the question. Confirming whether something is compulsory or optional prevents absence issues."},
          {id:"ac028",type:"error",q:"Can you tell to me the exact date for the parent-teacher evening?",a:"Can you tell me the exact date of the parent-teacher evening?",exp:"'Tell me' does not take 'to' between verb and object. 'Date of' (not 'for') the event. These preposition errors are common for Chinese speakers."},
          {id:"ac029",type:"fill",q:"When you say we need to '___ our data', do you mean entering results into SCOUT or creating our own ___?",a:"analyse ... spreadsheets",exp:"SCOUT is the NSW Department of Education data analysis tool. Clarifying the specific platform prevents wasted effort on the wrong task."},
          {id:"ac030",type:"mc",q:"Your head teacher gives you feedback: 'Your lesson lacked rigour.' You're unsure what they mean. What do you say?",options:["Are you saying my lesson was bad?","Could you help me understand what 'rigour' would look like in this context? I'd like to improve.","I disagree.","OK, I'll try harder."],a:1,exp:"Asking for specific examples of 'rigour' turns vague feedback into actionable advice. It shows professionalism and a growth mindset."},
          {id:"ac031",type:"fill",q:"I appreciate the feedback. Could you ___ me an example of what a '___ lesson' would look like for this topic?",a:"give ... rigorous",exp:"Asking for a concrete example is the most effective way to turn abstract feedback into a clear action plan."},
          {id:"ac032",type:"error",q:"I don't understand what means 'scope and sequence'. Can you explain?",a:"I don't understand what 'scope and sequence' means. Could you explain?",exp:"Embedded question: 'what X means' not 'what means X'. 'Could you' is more polite than 'Can you' in professional contexts."},
          {id:"ac033",type:"fill",q:"So just to ___ \u2014 we are expected to ___ our programmes to NESA outcomes for every lesson?",a:"clarify ... align",exp:"'Align to NESA outcomes' means map your teaching to the syllabus. This is a legal requirement for NSW teachers."},
          {id:"ac034",type:"fill",q:"When you mentioned 'adjustments for ___ learners', were you referring to students with ___ plans or EAL/D students?",a:"diverse ... individual",exp:"'Diverse learners' can mean many things. Clarifying whether it refers to students with Individual Education Plans (IEPs) or EAL/D students helps target your response."},
          {id:"ac035",type:"mc",q:"You receive an email with unclear instructions. What is the best response?",options:["Reply all saying the email was confusing","Ignore the email and guess what to do","Reply privately: 'Thanks for this. Could I check \u2014 are we expected to complete both tasks, or just the first one?'","Forward the email to a friend complaining about it"],a:2,exp:"A private, specific clarification email is professional and efficient. It avoids embarrassing the sender and resolves the confusion quickly."}
        ]
      },

      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      // 4.3 Summarising & Reporting Back
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      {
        id: "summarising-reporting",
        title: "Summarising & Reporting Back",
        theory: "In meetings, you may be asked to summarise a discussion, report on a project, or update colleagues. Structure: key finding + details + next steps. Use transitions: 'So in summary...', 'The main takeaway is...', 'Going forward, we need to...'. Reports should be concise \u2014 Australian colleagues value brevity. Avoid repeating everything said; focus on decisions made, actions agreed, and who is responsible.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"sr001",type:"fill",q:"So in ___, the main issues raised were student ___ and inconsistent marking practices.",a:"summary ... engagement",exp:"'In summary' signals you are wrapping up key points. Naming the main issues shows you can extract the essential information from a discussion."},
          {id:"sr002",type:"mc",q:"Which is the best way to begin a verbal report to your faculty?",options:["So basically what happened was...","I'd like to update you on the progress of the Year 9 assessment review.","Um, I have some stuff to tell you about.","The principal told me to report back, so here goes."],a:1,exp:"'I'd like to update you on...' is clear, professional, and immediately tells the audience what the report is about."},
          {id:"sr003",type:"error",q:"The main takeaway from the meeting is we should to review our homework policy.",a:"The main takeaway from the meeting is that we should review our homework policy.",exp:"'Is that we should' needs the conjunction 'that'. No 'to' after 'should' (modal verb rule)."},
          {id:"sr004",type:"fill",q:"Going ___, we agreed that each faculty would ___ a representative to the working party.",a:"forward ... nominate",exp:"'Going forward' means from now on. 'Nominate a representative' is the formal term for selecting someone to serve on a committee."},
          {id:"sr005",type:"mc",q:"You need to report back on a professional learning workshop. Which structure is best?",options:["Tell everyone everything that happened chronologically","Share the key takeaways, how they apply to your school, and suggest next steps","Read out your notes word for word","Say 'It was good' and sit down"],a:1,exp:"Key takeaways + application + next steps is the most effective report structure. Chronological retelling is too long; 'It was good' is too vague."},
          {id:"sr006",type:"fill",q:"The key ___ from the workshop were the importance of explicit teaching and the use of ___ assessment strategies.",a:"takeaways ... formative",exp:"'Key takeaways' = main lessons learned. 'Formative assessment' = ongoing assessment for learning (not just of learning)."},
          {id:"sr007",type:"error",q:"I will now summarise what we have discuss in the meeting today.",a:"I will now summarise what we have discussed in the meeting today.",exp:"'Have discussed' = present perfect (have + past participle). 'Discuss' is the base form, not the past participle."},
          {id:"sr008",type:"fill",q:"To ___ up, we identified three priority areas: student wellbeing, ___ integration, and parent communication.",a:"sum ... technology",exp:"'To sum up' = to summarise. Listing three priority areas is a clear, memorable structure for reporting back."},
          {id:"sr009",type:"mc",q:"Which transition phrase is best for introducing the next steps?",options:["And then we said...","The action items are as follows...","I think maybe we should...","So yeah, that's about it."],a:1,exp:"'The action items are as follows' is clear and professional. It signals that specific tasks with responsibilities will be listed."},
          {id:"sr010",type:"fill",q:"The committee ___ that we should pilot the new attendance tracking system in ___ 2 before rolling it out school-wide.",a:"recommended ... Term",exp:"'Recommended' reports back a group decision. 'Pilot in Term 2' shows a phased approach. 'Rolling it out' means implementing broadly."},
          {id:"sr011",type:"open",q:"Write a brief verbal report summarising a faculty meeting about the new Year 8 assessment schedule.",a:"Just a quick update from our faculty meeting. We reviewed the Year 8 assessment schedule and agreed to spread the tasks more evenly across the term. The main change is that the research project has been moved from Week 6 to Week 9 to reduce the assessment load in the middle of term. Sarah has volunteered to update the scope and sequence, and we'll share the revised schedule with students by the end of next week.",exp:"Good reports: name the topic, state the key decision, explain the main change, identify who is responsible, and give a timeline."},
          {id:"sr012",type:"fill",q:"Three action items came out of the meeting. ___, we need to update the risk assessment. Secondly, we need to ___ parents about the schedule change.",a:"Firstly ... inform",exp:"'Firstly, secondly, thirdly' provides clear sequencing. 'Inform parents' is more professional than 'tell parents' in written or formal contexts."},
          {id:"sr013",type:"error",q:"The main point is about that we need more professional development for technology.",a:"The main point is that we need more professional development in technology.",exp:"'The main point is that' (no 'about'). 'Professional development in technology' (not 'for'). Preposition choice matters in professional communication."},
          {id:"sr014",type:"fill",q:"I've ___ a brief summary of the workshop, which I'll ___ via email after the meeting.",a:"prepared ... circulate",exp:"'Circulate' means distribute to all relevant people. It is more professional than 'send around'. Preparing a written summary shows thoroughness."},
          {id:"sr015",type:"mc",q:"You are reporting back on a conference. What should you NOT include?",options:["Key ideas relevant to your school","Practical strategies you can share","Every single slide from every presentation","Suggested next steps for your team"],a:2,exp:"Reporting every detail is unhelpful and time-consuming. Focus on what is relevant and actionable for your specific audience."},
          {id:"sr016",type:"fill",q:"The professional learning focused on the Quality Teaching Framework, ___ on the elements of intellectual ___ and significance.",a:"specifically ... quality",exp:"The Quality Teaching Framework (QTF) has three dimensions: Intellectual Quality, Quality Learning Environment, and Significance. It is a key NSW pedagogical model."},
          {id:"sr017",type:"error",q:"We were decided that the excursion will be postponed to next term.",a:"We decided that the excursion would be postponed until next term.",exp:"'We decided' (active, not passive). 'Would be postponed' (future in the past). 'Until next term' (not 'to next term')."},
          {id:"sr018",type:"fill",q:"In terms of ___ steps, we agreed to reconvene in two weeks to ___ progress on the action items.",a:"next ... review",exp:"'In terms of next steps' transitions to the forward-looking part of a report. 'Reconvene' means meet again."},
          {id:"sr019",type:"fill",q:"The data ___ that Year 9 students are underperforming in writing compared to ___ benchmarks.",a:"shows ... state",exp:"'The data shows' uses evidence to support a finding. 'State benchmarks' refers to NSW-level performance data."},
          {id:"sr020",type:"mc",q:"How should you attribute ideas when reporting back on a group discussion?",options:["Name everyone who spoke and what they said","Say 'The group agreed that...' for consensus items and note any unresolved points","Take credit for all good ideas","Don't mention anyone by name ever"],a:1,exp:"'The group agreed' captures consensus. Noting unresolved items ensures nothing is lost. It is collaborative, not self-promoting."},
          {id:"sr021",type:"fill",q:"Just to ___ everyone up to speed \u2014 since the last meeting, we've ___ the parent survey and received 85 responses.",a:"bring ... completed",exp:"'Bring everyone up to speed' means update people on what has happened. It is a common meeting phrase in Australian English."},
          {id:"sr022",type:"error",q:"The feedback from parents was very positive, and most of them are satisfy with the new report format.",a:"The feedback from parents was very positive, and most of them are satisfied with the new report format.",exp:"'Are satisfied' (past participle as adjective, not base form 'satisfy'). This is a common error because Chinese adjectives don't change form."},
          {id:"sr023",type:"fill",q:"The ___ outcomes of the review are that we need a clearer behaviour management ___ and more consistent communication with parents.",a:"key ... framework",exp:"'Key outcomes' = most important results. 'Behaviour management framework' = structured approach to managing student behaviour."},
          {id:"sr024",type:"open",q:"Write a summary email to your head teacher about a professional learning event you attended on STEM education.",a:"Hi David, I wanted to update you on the STEM professional learning session I attended on Thursday. The main focus was on integrating computational thinking across KLAs, not just in Maths and Science. Three key takeaways were: first, start with unplugged activities before moving to digital tools; second, use real-world problems from local contexts; and third, build in regular reflection time for students. I think we could trial some of these approaches in our Year 7 Technology programme next term. Happy to present a five-minute overview at the next faculty meeting if that would be useful. Kind regards, Yunshu",exp:"A good summary email: states the event, identifies key takeaways, suggests application, and offers follow-up. It is concise and action-oriented."},
          {id:"sr025",type:"fill",q:"To ___ what we covered today: we reviewed the assessment data, ___ three areas for improvement, and assigned action items.",a:"recap ... identified",exp:"'Recap' is a shorter synonym for summarise, common in Australian meetings. Listing the meeting's three main activities gives a clear summary structure."},
          {id:"sr026",type:"error",q:"I would like to report about the progress of our literacy initiative.",a:"I would like to report on the progress of our literacy initiative.",exp:"'Report on' (not 'report about'). This is a fixed preposition combination in professional English."},
          {id:"sr027",type:"fill",q:"The committee ___ unanimously to proceed with the renovation of the science ___.",a:"voted ... laboratories",exp:"'Voted unanimously' means everyone agreed. 'Laboratories' is the formal word; 'labs' is acceptable in informal speech."},
          {id:"sr028",type:"mc",q:"Which closing statement is best after reporting back on a workshop?",options:["That's all I've got.","If anyone would like more details or the handout materials, please let me know.","It was a waste of time, honestly.","I think that covers it. Moving on..."],a:1,exp:"Offering to share materials invites further engagement and positions you as a resource. It is generous and professional."},
          {id:"sr029",type:"fill",q:"The main ___ was around whether to adopt a new learning management ___ or continue with Google Classroom.",a:"debate ... system",exp:"'The main debate was around' identifies the central disagreement. 'Learning management system' (LMS) is a key educational technology term."},
          {id:"sr030",type:"fill",q:"Overall, the professional learning was well ___, and I'd recommend it for anyone working on ___ integration.",a:"received ... technology",exp:"'Well received' means people responded positively. Making a recommendation shows leadership and initiative."},
          {id:"sr031",type:"error",q:"We have been agree to move the sports carnival to Week 10.",a:"We have agreed to move the sports carnival to Week 10.",exp:"'Have agreed' = present perfect active. 'Have been agree' is neither passive nor correct. Chinese speakers sometimes confuse passive and active voice."},
          {id:"sr032",type:"fill",q:"The ___ from the student wellbeing survey indicate that anxiety is a growing ___ among Year 10 students.",a:"findings ... concern",exp:"'Findings indicate' is a formal way to present data results. 'Growing concern' implies the issue is worsening and needs attention."},
          {id:"sr033",type:"mc",q:"You are asked to summarise a 90-minute meeting in 2 minutes. What do you focus on?",options:["Who attended and what they wore","Decisions made, actions agreed, and who is responsible","Every joke and anecdote shared during the meeting","Your personal opinions about everything discussed"],a:1,exp:"Decisions, actions, and responsibilities are the essential meeting outputs. Everything else is context that can be omitted in a brief summary."},
          {id:"sr034",type:"fill",q:"I'll send out the ___ of the meeting by the end of today so everyone has a written ___ of what was agreed.",a:"minutes ... record",exp:"'Minutes' = the official written summary of a meeting. 'Written record' emphasises the accountability function of minutes."},
          {id:"sr035",type:"open",q:"Write a brief verbal summary of a faculty discussion about adjusting the Year 10 assessment weighting.",a:"To summarise our discussion: we agreed that the current weighting of 40 per cent for the final exam is too high for Year 10. The proposal is to reduce it to 30 per cent and redistribute the remaining 10 per cent across two smaller in-class tasks. Michael will draft the revised assessment schedule, and we'll present it to the head teacher for approval by Friday.",exp:"Clear summary: states the problem, the proposed solution, who is responsible, and the timeline."},
          {id:"sr036",type:"fill",q:"There was general ___ that we need to improve the way we ___ student achievement data to parents.",a:"consensus ... communicate",exp:"'General consensus' means most people agreed. 'Communicate data to parents' is a key school improvement area in NSW."}
        ]
      },

      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      // 4.4 Polite Disagreement & Alternatives
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      {
        id: "professional-disagreement",
        title: "Polite Disagreement & Alternatives",
        theory: "Australian workplace culture values directness but with politeness. 'I see your point, but I wonder if...', 'That's interesting \u2014 have we considered...?', 'I respectfully disagree because...' are all appropriate. Avoid 'You're wrong' or passive silence. Offering an alternative when you disagree is seen as constructive. The goal is to challenge ideas, not people.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"pd001",type:"fill",q:"I see your ___, but I wonder if there might be a more ___ way to approach this.",a:"point ... effective",exp:"'I see your point' acknowledges the other person before disagreeing. 'I wonder if' softens the challenge. This is the classic Australian polite disagreement pattern."},
          {id:"pd002",type:"mc",q:"A colleague suggests cancelling all homework for Year 7. You disagree. Which response is best?",options:["That's the worst idea I've ever heard.","That's an interesting perspective. I do think homework has some value, though \u2014 perhaps we could look at reducing or redesigning it instead?","No. Homework is important.","Whatever you think is fine."],a:1,exp:"Acknowledging the idea ('interesting perspective'), stating your view ('I do think'), and offering an alternative ('reducing or redesigning') is constructive disagreement."},
          {id:"pd003",type:"error",q:"I am total disagree with this proposal because is too expensive.",a:"I totally disagree with this proposal because it is too expensive.",exp:"'Totally' is the adverb (not 'total'). 'Because it is' needs the subject pronoun 'it'. However, even corrected, 'I totally disagree' is quite blunt \u2014 softer phrasing is better."},
          {id:"pd004",type:"fill",q:"That's a ___ suggestion, but have we ___ the impact on students who rely on the bus service?",a:"fair ... considered",exp:"'Fair suggestion' validates the idea. 'Have we considered' invites the group to think about an angle that may have been missed."},
          {id:"pd005",type:"mc",q:"Which phrase is the LEAST appropriate for professional disagreement?",options:["I respectfully disagree because...","I take a slightly different view on this.","You clearly don't know what you're talking about.","I can see the merit in that, but I have some concerns."],a:2,exp:"'You clearly don't know what you're talking about' is a personal attack, not a professional disagreement. All other options challenge the idea, not the person."},
          {id:"pd006",type:"fill",q:"I ___ your concern, but I think we need to look at the data before ___ any conclusions.",a:"share ... drawing",exp:"'I share your concern' shows alignment on values. 'Before drawing any conclusions' urges evidence-based decision-making."},
          {id:"pd007",type:"error",q:"I don't think is a good idea to change the assessment task so close to the due date.",a:"I don't think it's a good idea to change the assessment task so close to the due date.",exp:"'I don't think it's' needs the contraction 'it's' (it is). Missing subjects are a frequent Chinese speaker error because Mandarin is a pro-drop language."},
          {id:"pd008",type:"fill",q:"I take a slightly different ___ on this. I believe the current approach is working, and we should give it more ___ before making changes.",a:"view ... time",exp:"'A slightly different view' is a gentle way to disagree. 'Give it more time' suggests patience rather than resistance."},
          {id:"pd009",type:"mc",q:"You disagree with your head teacher's suggestion in a meeting. What is the most professional approach?",options:["Stay silent and complain to colleagues later","Say 'I respect your position, and I'd like to offer an alternative perspective for the group to consider.'","Publicly challenge them to show you're not a pushover","Send a passive-aggressive email afterwards"],a:1,exp:"Respectfully offering an alternative in the meeting itself is the most professional approach. It is open, constructive, and brave."},
          {id:"pd010",type:"fill",q:"I appreciate the thought behind this, but my ___ is that it could create additional ___ for staff who are already stretched thin.",a:"concern ... workload",exp:"'My concern is that' frames disagreement around impact rather than personal preference. 'Workload' is a major issue in Australian teaching."},
          {id:"pd011",type:"fill",q:"That's one way to look at it. ___, I think the evidence suggests a different ___.",a:"However ... approach",exp:"'That's one way to look at it' acknowledges validity without agreeing. 'However' signals the contrast. 'The evidence suggests' is objective."},
          {id:"pd012",type:"error",q:"I am not agree because this idea will not success.",a:"I don't agree because this idea will not succeed.",exp:"'Don't agree' (not 'am not agree' \u2014 'agree' is not an adjective). 'Will not succeed' (verb) not 'success' (noun). Two common errors."},
          {id:"pd013",type:"open",q:"Write a polite disagreement with a proposal to eliminate recess for students who haven't completed homework.",a:"I understand the intention behind this \u2014 we want students to complete their homework. However, I have some concerns about removing recess as a consequence. Research shows that physical activity and social time are essential for learning and wellbeing, particularly for younger students. Could we consider an alternative approach, such as a supervised homework catch-up session during a free period instead? That way, students still get the break they need while also completing the work.",exp:"This response: acknowledges the intent, cites evidence, names the concern, and offers a concrete alternative. It challenges the idea without attacking the proposer."},
          {id:"pd014",type:"fill",q:"I ___ where you're coming from, but I'm not sure that approach would ___ in our context.",a:"understand ... work",exp:"'I understand where you're coming from' is empathetic. 'Not sure it would work in our context' is a pragmatic objection, not a personal one."},
          {id:"pd015",type:"mc",q:"What does 'Let's agree to disagree' mean?",options:["We hate each other now","We accept that we have different views and move on","One of us is right and the other is wrong","We should never discuss this topic again"],a:1,exp:"'Agree to disagree' means acknowledging a difference of opinion without needing to resolve it. It is a mature, professional response when consensus is not possible."},
          {id:"pd016",type:"fill",q:"With all due ___, I think we need to hear from the classroom teachers before the ___ makes a decision.",a:"respect ... executive",exp:"'With all due respect' is a formal disagreement opener. It warns the listener that a contrary view is coming. 'Executive' = school leadership team."},
          {id:"pd017",type:"error",q:"I think maybe we should to reconsider this decision before we going ahead.",a:"I think maybe we should reconsider this decision before we go ahead.",exp:"No 'to' after 'should'. 'Before we go ahead' (base form after 'before we', not gerund 'going'). Two modal/tense errors."},
          {id:"pd018",type:"fill",q:"Could I offer an ___ perspective? In my experience, this kind of initiative works better when it's ___-up rather than top-down.",a:"alternative ... bottom",exp:"'Alternative perspective' frames your view as an addition, not a rejection. 'Bottom-up' means driven by staff rather than imposed by leadership."},
          {id:"pd019",type:"fill",q:"I ___ the rationale, but I'm worried about the unintended ___ this might have on our EAL/D students.",a:"appreciate ... consequences",exp:"'I appreciate the rationale' is respectful. 'Unintended consequences' shows systems thinking \u2014 considering who might be negatively affected."},
          {id:"pd020",type:"mc",q:"A colleague suggests extending school hours. You disagree. Which response demonstrates best practice?",options:["Absolutely not.","I can see the appeal of more learning time. My concern, though, is that longer hours could lead to burnout for both students and staff. What if we focused on making the existing hours more productive instead?","That's ridiculous.","I guess if you think so."],a:1,exp:"This response acknowledges merit, names a specific concern, and proposes an alternative. It is the model for professional disagreement."},
          {id:"pd021",type:"fill",q:"I ___ that point, but I'd like to play devil's ___ for a moment. What happens if the students don't respond well to this change?",a:"take ... advocate",exp:"'Play devil's advocate' means deliberately argue the opposite position to test an idea. It is a valuable meeting skill that promotes critical thinking."},
          {id:"pd022",type:"error",q:"I respectful disagree with the suggestion to remove elective subjects.",a:"I respectfully disagree with the suggestion to remove elective subjects.",exp:"'Respectfully' is the adverb modifying 'disagree'. 'Respectful' is the adjective. This distinction doesn't exist in Chinese."},
          {id:"pd023",type:"fill",q:"Rather than scrapping the whole programme, could we look at ___ the elements that aren't ___ and keeping the rest?",a:"modifying ... working",exp:"'Rather than scrapping' offers a less extreme option. 'Modifying elements' is more nuanced than all-or-nothing thinking."},
          {id:"pd024",type:"fill",q:"I'm not ___ convinced that this is the right time to implement such a big change, given the ___ we're already managing.",a:"entirely ... workload",exp:"'Not entirely convinced' is a measured, diplomatic way to express doubt. 'Given the workload' provides a practical reason."},
          {id:"pd025",type:"mc",q:"After politely disagreeing in a meeting, your idea is rejected. What should you do?",options:["Refuse to cooperate with the final decision","Accept the group's decision gracefully and support implementation","Complain to other colleagues about it","Bring it up again at every future meeting"],a:1,exp:"Accepting the decision and supporting it shows professionalism. You voiced your concern \u2014 now the group has decided. Undermining the decision is unprofessional."},
          {id:"pd026",type:"fill",q:"I hear what you're saying, and I agree with the ___ principle. My only ___ is about the implementation timeline.",a:"underlying ... reservation",exp:"'Underlying principle' = the core idea. 'My only reservation' = the one thing I'm unsure about. This shows nuanced disagreement."},
          {id:"pd027",type:"error",q:"I am not comfortable about this idea because I think it will affect negative to the students.",a:"I'm not comfortable with this idea because I think it will affect the students negatively.",exp:"'Comfortable with' (not 'about'). 'Affect the students negatively' (adverb at end, not adjective). 'Affect negative' is a Chinese grammar pattern transfer."},
          {id:"pd028",type:"fill",q:"That's worth ___, but before we commit, could we look at what other schools have ___ with a similar approach?",a:"considering ... done",exp:"'Worth considering' validates the idea. 'What other schools have done' suggests learning from others before committing \u2014 evidence-based caution."},
          {id:"pd029",type:"open",q:"Write a polite disagreement with a plan to remove hands-on practical activities from Technology lessons to save time.",a:"I appreciate the concern about time pressures in the Technology curriculum. However, I'd like to suggest that practical activities are actually central to how students learn in this KLA. The NESA syllabus specifically requires students to develop practical skills through hands-on projects. Perhaps instead of removing them, we could look at integrating theory and practice more efficiently \u2014 for example, using design briefs that combine both research and making. That way, we save time without sacrificing the practical learning that defines the subject.",exp:"This response references the syllabus (NESA), provides pedagogical reasoning, and offers a concrete alternative that addresses the time concern."},
          {id:"pd030",type:"fill",q:"I'm ___ to push back a little on this. I don't think a one-size-fits-all approach will ___ the diverse needs of our students.",a:"going ... meet",exp:"'Going to push back a little' signals clear disagreement in advance. 'One-size-fits-all' is a common idiom meaning a single approach for everyone. 'Meet the needs' is a key education collocation."},
          {id:"pd031",type:"fill",q:"Could we ___ a middle ground? Perhaps we could trial the new approach with one year group and ___ the impact before expanding it.",a:"find ... evaluate",exp:"'Find a middle ground' means compromise between two positions. 'Trial and evaluate' is a pragmatic, evidence-based approach."}
        ]
      }
    ]
  };

  // ============================================================
  // MODULE 5: WRITTEN PROFESSIONAL REFLECTIONS
  // ============================================================
  WORKPLACE_ENGLISH.writtenReflections = {
    title: "Written Professional Reflections",
    sections: [
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      // 5.1 Lesson Reflections & Self-Evaluation
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      {
        id: "lesson-reflections",
        title: "Lesson Reflections & Self-Evaluation",
        theory: "Reflective practice is central to Australian teaching. NSW requires teachers to reflect on their practice using the Australian Professional Standards for Teachers. Good reflections follow the What\u2013So What\u2013Now What model: describe what happened, analyse why, plan what to change. Use action verbs: 'implemented', 'adapted', 'modified', 'observed', 'identified'. Reflections should be honest and specific, not generic or self-congratulatory.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"lr001",type:"fill",q:"In today's lesson, I ___ a collaborative design task. Students were ___ and most groups completed the brief on time.",a:"implemented ... engaged",exp:"'Implemented' is more professional than 'did'. 'Engaged' is a key descriptor for reflective writing in Australian education."},
          {id:"lr002",type:"mc",q:"Which reflection follows the What-So What-Now What model?",options:["The lesson was good.","Students completed the task. The high engagement was likely due to the real-world context. Next time, I'll add more scaffolding for EAL/D learners.","I taught about sustainability.","I need to be a better teacher."],a:1,exp:"Option 1 describes what happened (What), analyses why (So What), and plans a change (Now What). This three-part structure is the gold standard."},
          {id:"lr003",type:"error",q:"The students was very exciting when they saw the 3D printer.",a:"The students were very excited when they saw the 3D printer.",exp:"'Students were' (plural subject). 'Excited' (past participle adjective) not 'exciting' (present participle = the thing causing excitement). 'The students were exciting' would mean they excited others."},
          {id:"lr004",type:"fill",q:"I ___ that several students struggled with the written component, which suggests I need to provide more ___ for academic writing.",a:"observed ... scaffolding",exp:"'Observed' is a reflective verb. 'Scaffolding' means structured support to help students build skills gradually \u2014 a key concept in NSW pedagogy."},
          {id:"lr005",type:"mc",q:"Which action verb is most appropriate for reflective writing?",options:["Did","Adapted my questioning technique to elicit deeper responses","Tried stuff","Worked hard"],a:1,exp:"'Adapted my questioning technique to elicit deeper responses' uses precise action verbs. Generic words like 'did' or 'tried' lack the specificity needed in reflections."},
          {id:"lr006",type:"fill",q:"The ___ activity was less effective than planned because students lacked prior ___ of the key vocabulary.",a:"group ... knowledge",exp:"Identifying why something did not work is the 'So What' step. 'Lacked prior knowledge' is a specific, evidence-based reason."},
          {id:"lr007",type:"error",q:"I am satisfy with the lesson because the students enjoy it very much.",a:"I am satisfied with the lesson because the students enjoyed it very much.",exp:"'Satisfied' (adjective from past participle) not 'satisfy' (verb). 'Enjoyed' (past tense) for a completed lesson. These errors come from Chinese lacking verb conjugation."},
          {id:"lr008",type:"fill",q:"Next time, I will ___ the task instructions by adding visual ___ and worked examples on the board.",a:"modify ... cues",exp:"'Modify' = adjust something that exists. 'Visual cues' = images, diagrams, or icons that support understanding. This is a concrete 'Now What' plan."},
          {id:"lr009",type:"open",q:"Write a reflection on a lesson where classroom management was challenging.",a:"Today's Year 8 lesson on circuit design was disrupted by off-task behaviour from several students during the practical component. I observed that the transitions between activities were too slow, which created gaps where students lost focus. On reflection, I should have set clearer time limits and used a countdown timer visible on the board. Additionally, the instructions were verbal only, and some students may have needed a written checklist. Going forward, I will prepare a task card for each station and practise tighter transitions. I will also consider seating arrangements to separate students who tend to distract each other.",exp:"This reflection: describes what happened honestly, analyses contributing factors, and plans specific changes. It does not blame students but takes professional responsibility."},
          {id:"lr010",type:"fill",q:"This lesson ___ to Standard 1.5 of the Australian Professional Standards for Teachers, which focuses on ___ students' diverse linguistic backgrounds.",a:"relates ... understanding",exp:"Linking reflections to the Standards demonstrates professional awareness. Standard 1.5 is about differentiating teaching for diverse students including EAL/D learners."},
          {id:"lr011",type:"mc",q:"Which is the most reflective statement?",options:["The lesson went well.","I noticed that when I used think-pair-share, participation increased compared to whole-class questioning, particularly among quieter students.","Students did the work.","I covered all the content I planned."],a:1,exp:"Noticing a pattern (think-pair-share increased participation), comparing it to an alternative (whole-class questioning), and identifying who benefited (quieter students) is deep reflection."},
          {id:"lr012",type:"fill",q:"I need to ___ my approach to formative assessment. Currently, I am relying too heavily on ___ observation without recording data systematically.",a:"strengthen ... informal",exp:"'Strengthen my approach' = improve. 'Informal observation' is valid but needs to be systematic. This is a common area for growth in early-career teachers."},
          {id:"lr013",type:"error",q:"The lesson was not go as planned because the technology was not work properly.",a:"The lesson did not go as planned because the technology was not working properly.",exp:"'Did not go' (past simple negative). 'Was not working' (past continuous \u2014 ongoing state during the lesson). Chinese lacks these tense distinctions."},
          {id:"lr014",type:"fill",q:"On ___, the pacing of the lesson was too fast for the lower-ability students. I will slow down and include more ___ points next time.",a:"reflection ... check-in",exp:"'On reflection' = after thinking about it. 'Check-in points' = moments where the teacher pauses to assess understanding. This supports differentiation."},
          {id:"lr015",type:"fill",q:"I ___ the learning intentions with students at the start of the lesson, which helped them understand what they were working ___.",a:"shared ... towards",exp:"'Shared the learning intentions' is a key practice in Australian pedagogy. 'Working towards' shows goal-oriented learning."},
          {id:"lr016",type:"mc",q:"In reflective writing, what does 'evidence of student learning' mean?",options:["That students were present in the classroom","Observable indicators such as student work samples, exit tickets, or verbal responses that show understanding","The teacher's feeling about how the lesson went","The number of worksheets completed"],a:1,exp:"Evidence of learning must be observable and specific. Feelings and attendance are not evidence. Work samples and responses demonstrate actual understanding."},
          {id:"lr017",type:"fill",q:"I will ___ this reflection with the evidence from student exit tickets, which showed that 70 per cent of students could ___ the key concept correctly.",a:"support ... explain",exp:"Using quantitative data ('70 per cent') to support reflections makes them evidence-based rather than anecdotal."},
          {id:"lr018",type:"error",q:"I think the students was able to achieved the learning outcome successfully.",a:"I think the students were able to achieve the learning outcome successfully.",exp:"'Students were' (plural). 'Able to achieve' (to + base form, not past participle). 'Learning outcome' is the standard Australian term."},
          {id:"lr019",type:"fill",q:"A key ___ from this lesson is that students respond better when they can see the ___ of the task to their own lives.",a:"takeaway ... relevance",exp:"'Key takeaway' = most important lesson learned. 'Relevance to their own lives' connects to the Significance dimension of the Quality Teaching Framework."},
          {id:"lr020",type:"fill",q:"I ___ to differentiate the task by providing three levels of complexity. The extension students ___ the open-ended challenge enthusiastically.",a:"attempted ... tackled",exp:"'Attempted to differentiate' is honest \u2014 it doesn't claim perfection. 'Tackled enthusiastically' describes specific student behaviour."},
          {id:"lr021",type:"open",q:"Write a 'Now What' reflection paragraph after a lesson where technology failed mid-lesson.",a:"Going forward, I need to have a contingency plan for when technology fails during lessons. Next time I use the 3D printers, I will prepare an alternative unplugged activity that covers the same learning outcomes. I will also check all equipment the day before and have a troubleshooting guide printed at each station. Additionally, I could ask the IT support team to do a brief check-up on the printers before the lesson. This experience reminded me that over-reliance on technology without a backup plan creates unnecessary disruption.",exp:"The Now What section: plans specific changes, identifies resources needed, and reflects on the broader lesson learned."},
          {id:"lr022",type:"fill",q:"This lesson ___ me to align my assessment task with the NESA syllabus outcome TEC4-10TP, which requires students to ___ and justify a design solution.",a:"enabled ... evaluate",exp:"Referencing specific NESA outcome codes (e.g., TEC4-10TP) shows curriculum literacy. 'Evaluate and justify' are higher-order thinking verbs."},
          {id:"lr023",type:"error",q:"The students feedback suggest that they want more hand-on activities in the future.",a:"The students' feedback suggests that they want more hands-on activities in the future.",exp:"'Students' feedback' needs possessive apostrophe. 'Suggests' (third person singular). 'Hands-on' is hyphenated and plural."},
          {id:"lr024",type:"fill",q:"I identified a gap in my ___ knowledge of Aboriginal perspectives, which I will ___ through targeted professional learning this term.",a:"content ... address",exp:"Identifying gaps honestly is a sign of professional growth. 'Address through professional learning' shows a proactive plan. Aboriginal perspectives are embedded throughout the NSW curriculum."},
          {id:"lr025",type:"mc",q:"Which reflection shows the deepest level of analysis?",options:["The lesson was fine.","Students finished the task quickly, so I think it was too easy.","Three students didn't finish the task. Two of them are EAL/D learners who struggled with the written instructions. I need to provide bilingual glossaries and simplified task sheets as adjustments.","I gave them a worksheet and they did it."],a:2,exp:"Identifying who struggled, why they struggled (EAL/D + written instructions), and what specific adjustments to make (bilingual glossaries, simplified sheets) is the deepest analysis."},
          {id:"lr026",type:"fill",q:"My use of ___ feedback during the lesson was effective in redirecting students who were off task without ___ the learning flow.",a:"non-verbal ... disrupting",exp:"'Non-verbal feedback' = gestures, proximity, eye contact. 'Without disrupting the learning flow' shows awareness of lesson momentum."},
          {id:"lr027",type:"fill",q:"I ___ the lesson by gathering student voice data through an anonymous online poll, which ___ areas where students felt less confident.",a:"concluded ... revealed",exp:"'Concluded' = finished/ended. 'Revealed' = showed for the first time. Using student voice data in reflections is valued in NSW schools."},
          {id:"lr028",type:"error",q:"Next time I will to give more times for the students to complete their work.",a:"Next time I will give more time for the students to complete their work.",exp:"No 'to' after 'will' (modal verb rule). 'Time' is uncountable in this context (not 'times'). Both are common Chinese speaker errors."},
          {id:"lr029",type:"fill",q:"This reflection demonstrates my growth against Standard 3.1: ___ effective teaching strategies that are informed by an understanding of how students ___.",a:"Establish ... learn",exp:"Standard 3.1 of the Australian Professional Standards for Teachers focuses on establishing teaching strategies based on understanding of student learning."},
          {id:"lr030",type:"fill",q:"The ___ of this lesson was mixed. While the majority of students met the learning intention, a small group required additional ___ support.",a:"outcome ... one-on-one",exp:"'Mixed outcome' is an honest evaluation. 'One-on-one support' = individual help. Being specific about who needed help shows differentiation awareness."},
          {id:"lr031",type:"mc",q:"A good lesson reflection should always include:",options:["How well you got along with students","What you did, why it worked or didn't, and what you'll change","A list of resources used","How you felt emotionally"],a:1,exp:"What + Why + What next (What-So What-Now What) is the essential structure. Resources and feelings are supplementary, not central."},
          {id:"lr032",type:"fill",q:"I need to develop my confidence in providing ___ feedback that is specific and helps students understand their next steps for ___.",a:"written ... improvement",exp:"Giving specific written feedback is a skill that develops with practice. 'Next steps for improvement' = what the student should do to get better."},
          {id:"lr033",type:"error",q:"Reflecting about this lesson, I realise that I should have gave more clear instructions.",a:"Reflecting on this lesson, I realise that I should have given clearer instructions.",exp:"'Reflecting on' (not 'about'). 'Should have given' (past participle, not 'gave'). 'Clearer' (comparative adjective, not 'more clear')."},
          {id:"lr034",type:"fill",q:"I am ___ gathering a portfolio of evidence that demonstrates my progress towards achieving ___ at the Proficient level.",a:"currently ... accreditation",exp:"NSW teachers must achieve accreditation at the Proficient level through NESA. A portfolio of evidence is the key documentation method."},
          {id:"lr035",type:"open",q:"Write a brief self-evaluation paragraph linking a successful lesson to the Australian Professional Standards for Teachers.",a:"In today's Year 7 Technology lesson, I implemented a differentiated design challenge that catered to diverse learning needs, aligning with Standard 1.5 (Differentiate teaching to meet the specific learning needs of students across the full range of abilities). I provided three entry points: a scaffolded template for support learners, a standard brief for core learners, and an open-ended extension challenge. Evidence of effectiveness includes the high level of on-task behaviour observed and the quality of student design sketches, which I will include in my accreditation portfolio.",exp:"This self-evaluation: names the specific Standard, describes what was done, explains the differentiation approach, and identifies evidence for accreditation."}
        ]
      },

      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      // 5.2 Incident Reports & Documentation
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      {
        id: "incident-reports",
        title: "Incident Reports & Documentation",
        theory: "Incident reports must be factual, specific, and use objective language. Record who, what, when, where. Avoid subjective language ('he was being naughty'). Use 'Student A displayed off-task behaviour by...' or 'At 10:15, I observed...'. Accuracy matters for legal and welfare reasons. In NSW, incidents are typically recorded in Sentral. Reports may be used in meetings with parents, in welfare referrals, or in formal disciplinary processes.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"ir001",type:"fill",q:"At ___, I observed Student A leave their seat without permission and ___ towards the back of the classroom.",a:"10:15 ... walk",exp:"Recording the exact time is critical for incident reports. Objective verbs: 'leave', 'walk' \u2014 describe what you saw, not what you assumed."},
          {id:"ir002",type:"mc",q:"Which is the most appropriate language for an incident report?",options:["He was being a real troublemaker today.","Student B was observed using inappropriate language directed at Student C during Period 3.","She's always causing problems.","The kid went crazy in class."],a:1,exp:"Option 1 is objective: names who (Student B), what (inappropriate language), to whom (Student C), and when (Period 3). The others are subjective or informal."},
          {id:"ir003",type:"error",q:"The student was very naughty and made a big trouble in the classroom.",a:"The student displayed disruptive behaviour during the classroom activity.",exp:"'Naughty' and 'made a big trouble' are informal and subjective. 'Displayed disruptive behaviour' is the professional, objective equivalent. Incident reports must avoid judgmental language."},
          {id:"ir004",type:"fill",q:"I ___ the incident on Sentral and referred the matter to the ___ coordinator for follow-up.",a:"documented ... year",exp:"'Documented on Sentral' shows proper procedure. 'Year coordinator' is the staff member responsible for student welfare in that year group in NSW schools."},
          {id:"ir005",type:"mc",q:"Which detail is LEAST important in an incident report?",options:["The time the incident occurred","What the student was wearing","The specific behaviour observed","Who else was present or witnessed the incident"],a:1,exp:"What the student was wearing is generally irrelevant unless it is part of the incident (e.g., uniform breach). Time, behaviour, and witnesses are essential details."},
          {id:"ir006",type:"fill",q:"Student C ___ to follow the instruction to return to their seat. I used a calm, firm tone and offered a ___ of staying or moving to a quiet space.",a:"refused ... choice",exp:"'Refused to follow the instruction' is factual. 'Offered a choice' demonstrates that a positive behaviour strategy was used before escalation."},
          {id:"ir007",type:"error",q:"I think the student is having a mental health problem because they always look sad.",a:"I have observed that the student has appeared withdrawn on several occasions and have referred this concern to the school counsellor.",exp:"Teachers should not diagnose mental health conditions. Instead, describe observable behaviour ('appeared withdrawn') and refer to qualified professionals ('school counsellor')."},
          {id:"ir008",type:"fill",q:"The incident ___ at approximately 11:30 during the transition between Periods 2 and 3 in the ___ corridor.",a:"occurred ... main",exp:"'Occurred at approximately' is formal and precise. 'During the transition' identifies the context. Location details are important for incident mapping."},
          {id:"ir009",type:"mc",q:"A student tells you they are being bullied. What should you document?",options:["Only what you personally witnessed","What the student told you, using their exact words where possible, and any actions you took","Your opinion about who is at fault","Nothing \u2014 just tell the student it will be fine"],a:1,exp:"Document what the student said (in their words), what you observed, and what actions you took. Do not investigate or assign blame \u2014 that is for the welfare team."},
          {id:"ir010",type:"fill",q:"The student ___ that they had been receiving threatening messages from another student via social media. I ___ this to the head teacher immediately.",a:"disclosed ... reported",exp:"'Disclosed' is the formal term for when a student shares sensitive information. 'Reported immediately' shows you followed mandatory reporting procedures."},
          {id:"ir011",type:"open",q:"Write an incident report about a student who damaged school equipment during a Technology lesson.",a:"Date: 15 March 2026. Time: 1:45 PM. Location: Room T3. During a Year 8 Technology practical, Student D struck the 3D printer repeatedly with a ruler after becoming frustrated with a printing error. The printer sustained damage to the extruder assembly. I instructed Student D to step away from the equipment and sit at a separate desk. I spoke to Student D calmly and asked what had happened. Student D stated they were upset because their project had failed to print correctly. I contacted the year coordinator, Mr Thompson, who collected Student D at 1:55 PM. I logged the incident on Sentral and notified the Technology head teacher about the equipment damage.",exp:"Good incident report: date, time, location, factual sequence, student's own words, actions taken, who was contacted, and where it was documented."},
          {id:"ir012",type:"fill",q:"I ___ the student a verbal warning and recorded the ___ on Sentral as a Level 1 behaviour incident.",a:"issued ... interaction",exp:"'Issued a verbal warning' is formal documentation language. 'Level 1 behaviour incident' refers to the behaviour management levels used in many NSW schools."},
          {id:"ir013",type:"error",q:"The student was act aggressive and I think he wanted to hurt someone.",a:"The student displayed aggressive behaviour, including raised voice and clenched fists.",exp:"'Displayed aggressive behaviour' is objective. 'Including raised voice and clenched fists' describes observable evidence. 'I think he wanted to hurt someone' is an assumption \u2014 never include assumptions in reports."},
          {id:"ir014",type:"fill",q:"Following the incident, I contacted the student's ___ by phone at 3:30 PM to ___ them of the situation and the school's response.",a:"parent ... inform",exp:"'Contacted the parent' documents communication. 'Inform them of the situation and the school's response' is professional language for parent notification."},
          {id:"ir015",type:"mc",q:"When writing an incident report, why should you avoid the word 'always' (e.g., 'He always disrupts the class')?",options:["It's grammatically incorrect","It's an absolute statement that is unlikely to be true and could be challenged","It's too formal","Teachers aren't allowed to use that word"],a:1,exp:"'Always' is an absolute that is almost never accurate. It can be challenged by parents or in formal processes. Use 'frequently' or 'on multiple occasions' with dates."},
          {id:"ir016",type:"fill",q:"No physical ___ was observed. However, Student E appeared visibly ___ and was supported by the school counsellor.",a:"injury ... distressed",exp:"'No physical injury observed' is an important factual detail. 'Visibly distressed' describes an emotional state objectively."},
          {id:"ir017",type:"error",q:"The student fight with another student and both of them get hurt.",a:"The student was involved in a physical altercation with another student, and both sustained minor injuries.",exp:"'Physical altercation' is the professional term. 'Sustained minor injuries' is more precise than 'get hurt'. Past tense ('was involved', 'sustained') is required."},
          {id:"ir018",type:"fill",q:"I ___ a restorative conversation between the two students during lunch, facilitated by the ___ coordinator.",a:"organised ... wellbeing",exp:"'Restorative conversation' is a specific approach used in NSW schools to repair relationships after conflict. 'Wellbeing coordinator' manages student welfare."},
          {id:"ir019",type:"fill",q:"The student was ___ from the classroom at 2:10 PM and placed on internal ___ for the remainder of the day.",a:"removed ... suspension",exp:"'Removed from the classroom' is the factual description. 'Internal suspension' means the student stays at school but is separated from regular classes."},
          {id:"ir020",type:"mc",q:"Which statement is appropriately objective for an incident report?",options:["Student F is a bad influence on others.","Student F was observed encouraging three other students to leave the classroom without permission.","Student F is always up to no good.","I don't like Student F's attitude."],a:1,exp:"'Was observed encouraging three other students to leave without permission' is specific, factual, and objective. It describes actions, not character."},
          {id:"ir021",type:"fill",q:"Under the school's ___ reporting obligations, I reported the disclosure to the principal ___ as required by NSW legislation.",a:"mandatory ... immediately",exp:"Mandatory reporting is a legal obligation for NSW teachers under the Children and Young Persons (Care and Protection) Act 1998. Immediate reporting to the principal is required."},
          {id:"ir022",type:"error",q:"I recorded the incident on Sentral and sent an email to the parent to inform about what happen.",a:"I recorded the incident on Sentral and sent an email to the parent to inform them about what happened.",exp:"'Inform them' needs the pronoun object. 'What happened' uses past tense. These are common omissions for Chinese speakers."},
          {id:"ir023",type:"fill",q:"The ___ was resolved through a mediated discussion, and both students agreed to a behaviour ___ going forward.",a:"conflict ... contract",exp:"'Behaviour contract' is a formal agreement between the student and the school outlining expected behaviour and consequences."},
          {id:"ir024",type:"open",q:"Write a Sentral entry for a student who was caught using their phone during an exam.",a:"Date: 18 March 2026. Period 4 (1:15 PM). Location: Hall. During the Year 10 Science exam, I observed Student G using a mobile phone concealed under their exam paper. I approached Student G and quietly asked them to hand over the device. Student G complied without protest. I confiscated the phone and placed it in the staffroom. I notified the exam supervisor, Ms Chen, and recorded the incident. The exam paper was collected separately for review by the head teacher. Student G's parent was contacted at 3:00 PM by the year coordinator.",exp:"Exam incidents require precise documentation: time, location, what was observed, what action was taken, and who was notified. The language is entirely factual."},
          {id:"ir025",type:"fill",q:"I followed the school's ___ procedure and escorted the students to the ___ point as directed by the emergency announcement.",a:"emergency ... assembly",exp:"Emergency procedures and assembly points are part of the school's Work Health and Safety plan. Documenting compliance is important."},
          {id:"ir026",type:"error",q:"The student said he don't want to do the work because it is too boring for him.",a:"The student stated that he did not want to complete the work, describing the task as unengaging.",exp:"'Stated' is more formal than 'said'. 'Did not want to complete' is past tense. Paraphrase the student's words objectively \u2014 'boring' becomes 'unengaging' or use the student's exact words in quotation marks."},
          {id:"ir027",type:"fill",q:"This is the third ___ of similar behaviour from Student H this term. I have referred the ___ to the learning support team for further assessment.",a:"instance ... matter",exp:"'Third instance' documents a pattern without exaggeration. 'Referred the matter to the learning support team' shows appropriate escalation."},
          {id:"ir028",type:"mc",q:"A student's parent calls to dispute an incident report. What should you do?",options:["Change the report to keep the parent happy","Explain that the report documents what you observed and offer to arrange a meeting with the year coordinator","Argue with the parent on the phone","Delete the report from Sentral"],a:1,exp:"Incident reports are factual records and should not be altered. Offering a meeting is professional and allows for further discussion with appropriate support."},
          {id:"ir029",type:"fill",q:"The student ___ a verbal threat towards me, stating: 'You can't make me do anything.' I remained ___ and applied the de-escalation protocol.",a:"made ... calm",exp:"Recording exact quotes in speech marks is important. 'Remained calm and applied the de-escalation protocol' documents your professional response."},
          {id:"ir030",type:"fill",q:"A ___ safety check of the workshop revealed that two soldering irons had been left ___ and unattended by students.",a:"routine ... switched on",exp:"'Routine safety check' = regular inspection. 'Left switched on and unattended' is a WHS (Work Health and Safety) concern that must be documented."},
          {id:"ir031",type:"error",q:"Student's parent was very angry and shouting in the phone to me.",a:"The student's parent expressed frustration during a phone conversation with me.",exp:"'Expressed frustration' is objective and professional. 'Very angry and shouting in the phone to me' is informal and subjective. 'During a phone conversation with me' is correct phrasing."},
          {id:"ir032",type:"fill",q:"I have ___ this incident to my line manager and ___ a copy of the report for my personal records.",a:"escalated ... retained",exp:"'Escalated' means referred to a higher authority. 'Retained a copy' means kept a copy. Both are important for professional self-protection."},
          {id:"ir033",type:"fill",q:"The student was ___ back to class after a 15-minute cool-down period. I checked in with the student at the end of the ___ to ensure they were settled.",a:"returned ... lesson",exp:"'Returned to class' and 'checked in' show a complete resolution cycle. Following up demonstrates duty of care."},
          {id:"ir034",type:"mc",q:"What is the primary purpose of documenting incidents on Sentral?",options:["To punish students","To create an accurate record that supports student welfare, safety, and accountability","To give teachers evidence to use against students","To show the principal how hard teachers work"],a:1,exp:"Incident documentation supports welfare and accountability. It is not punitive \u2014 it creates a factual record that helps all parties, including the student."},
          {id:"ir035",type:"open",q:"Write a brief welfare referral note for a student who has been consistently withdrawn and disengaged over the past two weeks.",a:"I am referring Student J for a welfare check. Over the past two weeks, I have observed the following changes in behaviour: Student J has been arriving late to class on five occasions, has not submitted three consecutive homework tasks, and has been sitting alone at lunch instead of with their usual friendship group. During class, Student J appears withdrawn, avoids eye contact, and responds to questions with minimal answers. I asked Student J if everything was okay, and they replied, 'I'm fine.' Given the pattern of change, I believe a check-in with the school counsellor would be appropriate. I have logged all observations on Sentral.",exp:"A welfare referral: names specific, observable changes over a clear timeframe, notes what the teacher has already done, and recommends an appropriate next step."}
        ]
      },

      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      // 5.3 Setting Professional Goals (PDPs)
      // ----------------------------------------------------------
      {
        id: "professional-goals",
        title: "Setting Professional Goals (PDPs)",
        theory: "NSW teachers complete a Professional Development Plan (PDP) aligned to the Australian Professional Standards for Teachers. Goals should be SMART: Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound. Common areas: differentiation, technology integration, assessment literacy, cultural responsiveness. PDPs are discussed with your supervisor and reviewed annually. They drive your professional growth and support your journey towards accreditation at the Proficient level.",
        exercises: [
          {id:"pg001",type:"fill",q:"My professional goal for this term is to ___ my use of formative assessment strategies to better ___ student understanding during lessons.",a:"strengthen ... gauge",exp:"'Strengthen my use' implies improvement of an existing practice. 'Gauge student understanding' means measure/check how well students are learning."},
          {id:"pg002",type:"mc",q:"Which goal is SMART?",options:["Be a better teacher","Improve student engagement","By the end of Term 2, implement exit tickets in 80% of my Year 7 Technology lessons and analyse the data to inform my planning.","Try to use more technology"],a:2,exp:"Option 2 is Specific (exit tickets, Year 7 Technology), Measurable (80%), Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound (end of Term 2). The others are vague."},
          {id:"pg003",type:"error",q:"I want to improve my teaching because I am not enough good.",a:"I want to improve my teaching practice in the area of differentiation to better meet the needs of diverse learners.",exp:"'Not enough good' is both grammatically wrong and unnecessarily self-critical. PDPs should be positive and specific \u2014 name the area of growth and the purpose."},
          {id:"pg004",type:"fill",q:"This goal aligns with Standard 3.3 of the Australian Professional Standards: ___ teaching strategies that include a range of resources, including ICT, to ___ students in their learning.",a:"Using ... engage",exp:"Standard 3.3 focuses on using teaching strategies with varied resources. Linking PDP goals to specific Standards is a requirement in NSW."},
          {id:"pg005",type:"mc",q:"What does 'evidence of achievement' mean in a PDP?",options:["A photo of you teaching","Observable, documented proof that you have worked towards or achieved your goal","A statement from a friend that you're a good teacher","Your university transcript"],a:1,exp:"Evidence includes student work samples, lesson observations, professional learning certificates, reflective journal entries, or data showing improved outcomes."},
          {id:"pg006",type:"fill",q:"I will ___ my progress towards this goal by collecting student feedback surveys at the end of each ___ and comparing the results.",a:"measure ... unit",exp:"'Measure progress' makes the goal quantifiable. 'Student feedback surveys' provide concrete data. 'Each unit' sets the time frame."},
          {id:"pg007",type:"error",q:"My goal is to attend more professional learning session this year.",a:"My goal is to attend at least four professional learning sessions this year, focusing on technology integration in the classroom.",exp:"'More' is vague. 'At least four' is specific. 'Sessions' (plural). Adding the focus area makes it relevant and targeted."},
          {id:"pg008",type:"fill",q:"By the end of ___ 1, I aim to have developed a bank of differentiated resources for my Year 9 IST ___ that cater to support, core, and extension learners.",a:"Term ... class",exp:"Time-bound (end of Term 1), specific (differentiated resources), and measurable (bank of resources for three levels). This is a well-structured PDP goal."},
          {id:"pg009",type:"open",q:"Write a SMART professional goal about improving your classroom management skills.",a:"By the end of Term 2, I will implement a consistent positive behaviour management system in my Year 8 Technology classes, including clear expectations displayed in the classroom, a three-step redirection process, and a reward system for on-task behaviour. I will measure success by comparing Sentral behaviour data from Term 1 and Term 2, aiming for a 30 per cent reduction in recorded behaviour incidents. I will seek feedback from my mentor teacher through two classroom observations during the term.",exp:"SMART: Specific (positive behaviour system, three components), Measurable (30% reduction, two observations), Achievable, Relevant (Year 8 classes), Time-bound (end of Term 2)."},
          {id:"pg010",type:"fill",q:"I will seek ___ from my mentor teacher through regular classroom ___ to gather evidence of my growth in this area.",a:"feedback ... observations",exp:"'Seek feedback' is proactive. 'Classroom observations' by mentors or peers are a primary evidence source for PDPs in NSW schools."},
          {id:"pg011",type:"mc",q:"Which is NOT typically part of a PDP?",options:["Goals aligned to the Australian Professional Standards for Teachers","A timeline for achieving each goal","Your personal salary expectations","Evidence of professional learning activities"],a:2,exp:"PDPs focus on professional growth, not salary. Goals, timelines, Standards alignment, and evidence of learning are all standard PDP components."},
          {id:"pg012",type:"fill",q:"I plan to ___ a professional learning course on trauma-informed practice to better ___ students who have experienced adverse childhood events.",a:"complete ... support",exp:"'Trauma-informed practice' is increasingly important in Australian schools. This goal shows awareness of student welfare and willingness to develop specialist skills."},
          {id:"pg013",type:"error",q:"I will try to be more better at giving feedback to students.",a:"I will improve the quality of my written feedback by using specific, actionable comments linked to success criteria.",exp:"'More better' is a double comparative (wrong). The rewrite is specific about what aspect of feedback (written), how (specific, actionable), and the benchmark (success criteria)."},
          {id:"pg014",type:"fill",q:"This goal is ___ to Standard 5.2, which requires teachers to provide timely and ___ feedback to students about their learning.",a:"linked ... meaningful",exp:"Standard 5.2 focuses on feedback. 'Meaningful feedback' means it helps students understand what to do next, not just what they got wrong."},
          {id:"pg015",type:"fill",q:"I will ___ in peer observation with two colleagues this term to share ___ and learn from their teaching approaches.",a:"participate ... expertise",exp:"'Peer observation' is a key professional learning strategy in NSW schools. It is collaborative, not evaluative. 'Share expertise' is reciprocal."},
          {id:"pg016",type:"mc",q:"How often should PDP goals be reviewed in NSW?",options:["Once every five years","At least annually, with informal check-ins throughout the year","Only when the principal asks","Never \u2014 once set, they are permanent"],a:1,exp:"NSW PDPs are reviewed at least annually, but regular informal check-ins with your supervisor help keep you on track and allow adjustments."},
          {id:"pg017",type:"fill",q:"I aim to ___ my understanding of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander histories and cultures to ensure my teaching is culturally ___ and respectful.",a:"deepen ... responsive",exp:"'Culturally responsive' teaching is a priority in NSW education. 'Deepen my understanding' acknowledges this is an ongoing journey, not a one-off task."},
          {id:"pg018",type:"error",q:"My PDP goal is to learn about use technology in my teaching.",a:"My PDP goal is to learn how to integrate technology effectively into my teaching practice.",exp:"'Learn about use' is ungrammatical. 'Learn how to integrate technology effectively' is specific and uses professional language."},
          {id:"pg019",type:"fill",q:"As evidence of ___ towards this goal, I will compile a portfolio including lesson plans, student work ___, and reflective journal entries.",a:"progress ... samples",exp:"'Evidence of progress' is the key PDP phrase. A portfolio with multiple evidence types demonstrates thorough engagement with the goal."},
          {id:"pg020",type:"fill",q:"I will collaborate with the learning and support ___ to develop individual learning plans for three students with ___ needs in my classes.",a:"team ... additional",exp:"The Learning and Support Team (LaST) coordinates support for students with additional needs in NSW schools. Collaboration shows Standard 1.6 alignment."},
          {id:"pg021",type:"open",q:"Write a PDP goal about developing your skills in data-driven teaching.",a:"By the end of Semester 1, I will develop my ability to use student assessment data to inform my teaching decisions. Specifically, I will analyse formative and summative assessment results using SCOUT and Excel to identify patterns in student achievement across my Year 9 and Year 10 IST classes. I will use this data to adjust my teaching strategies for at least three lessons per term. Evidence will include annotated lesson plans showing data-informed modifications, SCOUT reports, and a reflective commentary. This goal aligns with Standard 5.4: Interpret student data.",exp:"Comprehensive SMART goal: tool-specific (SCOUT, Excel), measurable (three lessons per term), evidence-rich, and linked to Standard 5.4."},
          {id:"pg022",type:"fill",q:"I will ___ for feedback from students, parents, and colleagues to ___ my understanding of how my teaching is perceived and where I can improve.",a:"actively seek ... broaden",exp:"'Actively seek feedback' shows initiative. Gathering feedback from multiple stakeholders (students, parents, colleagues) provides a 360-degree view."},
          {id:"pg023",type:"error",q:"I hope to maybe possibly improve my skills in assessment if I have time.",a:"I will develop my assessment design skills by completing the NESA online module on assessment by the end of Term 1.",exp:"The original is vague and non-committal. 'I hope to maybe possibly' shows no clear intention. A PDP goal must be definite, specific, and time-bound."},
          {id:"pg024",type:"fill",q:"To support this goal, I will attend the school's professional learning ___ on differentiated instruction and apply the strategies in my ___ planning.",a:"workshop ... lesson",exp:"Attending professional learning and then applying it to planning shows a complete learning cycle. This is what NESA expects for accreditation evidence."},
          {id:"pg025",type:"mc",q:"Which evidence type is MOST valuable for demonstrating achievement of a PDP goal about student engagement?",options:["A selfie of you teaching","Before-and-after student engagement survey data showing measurable improvement","An email saying you attended a workshop","A lesson plan you never taught"],a:1,exp:"Before-and-after data shows measurable impact on practice. Attendance alone does not demonstrate learning, and untaught plans demonstrate nothing."},
          {id:"pg026",type:"fill",q:"My long-term professional ___ is to achieve accreditation at the Highly Accomplished level within the next five years, building on my current ___ at the Proficient level.",a:"aspiration ... accreditation",exp:"'Professional aspiration' = long-term career goal. The progression is: Graduate > Proficient > Highly Accomplished > Lead. Most NSW teachers aim for Proficient first."},
          {id:"pg027",type:"fill",q:"I will ___ a professional learning community with three colleagues to ___ share resources and discuss effective teaching practices fortnightly.",a:"establish ... collaboratively",exp:"'Establish a PLC' (Professional Learning Community) is a powerful professional growth strategy. 'Fortnightly' = every two weeks (common Australian term)."},
          {id:"pg028",type:"error",q:"I want to improve my communication skill with parent and colleague.",a:"I want to improve my communication skills with parents and colleagues.",exp:"'Skills' (plural), 'parents' (plural), 'colleagues' (plural). Chinese does not mark plurals, making this a persistent error pattern."},
          {id:"pg029",type:"fill",q:"This goal addresses an area identified in my most recent classroom ___ feedback, where my supervisor noted that I could improve the ___ of my questioning techniques.",a:"observation ... quality",exp:"Using observation feedback to set PDP goals shows a reflective, growth-oriented approach. 'Quality of questioning' is a common improvement area."},
          {id:"pg030",type:"open",q:"Write a PDP goal about embedding Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander perspectives across your teaching.",a:"By the end of this year, I will meaningfully embed Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander perspectives in at least one unit of work per term across my Year 7 and Year 8 Technology classes. I will achieve this by completing the Department's online cultural awareness training by the end of Term 1, consulting with the school's Aboriginal Education Officer to review my resources for cultural accuracy, and attending the local AECG meeting in Term 2. Evidence will include updated unit plans with embedded perspectives, student feedback on the relevance of the content, and a reflective journal entry per term. This goal aligns with Standards 1.4 and 2.4.",exp:"This goal is culturally respectful, involves consultation with appropriate community members (AEO, AECG), is time-bound, and links to two relevant Standards."}
        ]
      }
    ]
  };

})();
